It will make you a AWESOME personel defense pistol. At $325.00 it is the lowest priced one in the USA on armslist, PLUS  you get the holster, 2 mag pouch & ammo.  (THIS IS IN VERY GOOD / EXCELLENT CONDITION) (ITS MADE BY BERRTTA) if your interested please CALL REDACTEDTRANSFER WILL BE AT BILLS GUN SHOP IN WATERVILLENOTE: I'm selling due to health reasons but please dont waiste our time with low ball offers.NOTE: If you are interested, PLEASE CALL, I will not relpy to emails asking if its still available, if its still listed, IT IS STILL AVAILABLE .HERE IS MORE INFORMATION ABOUT THIS GREAT PISTOL : 

Background: The Beretta-created Stoeger 8000 Cougar semi-auto pistols inherit the reputation of the original Beretta 8000 as reliable, durable and powerful. First designed primarily for tactical undercover work, the Cougar is now carried by a growing number of police officers as their official duty sidearm thanks to its ergonomics, low recoil and inherent accuracy.  The goal was to be a smaller, more compact and concealable pistol for undercover and security work. The LAPD issued a variant of the Cougar with a 4" barrel for a time.

Beretta bought Stoeger for their skilled manufacturing employees and then shipped the original Beretta Cougar machines to Stoeger to continue making the famous Beretta Cougar pistol (which made room to make the PX4 model pistol).

In its new incarnation, Beretta developed an ergonomically-advanced pistol that is compact but capable of handling high-power cartridges, offering high magazine capacity and giving a long service life. This has been possible also thanks to the innovative adaptation of a locked-breech system with a rotating barrel. Today, the Stoeger 8000 Cougar pistol is manufactured by the Stoeger Silah Sanayi A.S., strictly in line with the most traditional Beretta quality control and attention to detail.    LOW RECOIL

Upon firing this pistol, shooters are amazed by the low felt recoil. This is due to two factors working together. The first is the rotating barrel system, which dissipates recoil radially rather than directing it into the shooter’s hand. The second is the central block, which absorbs the mechanical recoil from the barrel and the slide before this is transferred to the frame. When the Cougar is in battery, the positive lock-up of barrel to slide assures perfect alignment of barrel and sights. Upon firing, the barrel travels and rotates with axial movement. Besides low recoil, the result is superior accuracy and quicker recovery for follow-up shots.

ADVANCED ERGONOMICS FOR EASY HANDLING, CONTROL, CONCEALMENT

The Cougar is one of the most ergonomically advanced pistols in its class. The user-friendly, contoured frame and grips make the Cougar exceptionally easy to control during firing. By taking hand anatomy and instinctive hold into account, the Cougar accommodates smaller hands and also protects larger hands from being bitten by the slide. All edges are rounded or beveled, and are carefully finished to make the Cougar virtually snag-proof and exceptionally easy to draw and conceal.MORE FEATURES

Rotating barrel action: the barrel stays put while the slide travels backward, rotating approximately 30 degrees by means of a cam pin and tracked milled onto the barrel and frame that unlocks the barrel from the breech once a safe chamber pressure is reached. This enhances accuracy as the barrel stays pointed on target and does not travel to the rear and then slightly tip up at the muzzle as in many other designs.

All metal lower frame: In stark contrast to the polymers used by most other semi-auto handguns being sold today. No plastic guns here. Visible External Hammer – a real hammer like a real gun!Double action and single action.

Safeties: Safety and de-cocker are combined into a convenient single lever.  It is also AMBIDEXTROUS for right and left handed shooters.

Take down lever is easy to use for field stripping and cleaning Reversible magazine catch.  Sights: 3 dot sighting system easily acquire your target. Both front and rear sights are MILLED and DOVETAILED into the steel of slide for durability and easily visible.  Smooth trigger action. Clean, crisp let off when working the action.

postcontent: Let's get the important stuff out of the way.  The gun is in perfect mechanical condition.  It functions extremely well.  This is a hand me down from my father.  He was given the gun by a close friend in exchange for a place to stay back in the early 90's.  I do not know how many rounds the friend put through it.  My dad estimates he put about 100 rounds through it for the many years he owned it.  I put exactly 50 rounds through it.  Looking at the bore, it does not appear the original owner did a lot of shooting.  It's very likely the gun has less than 1000 rounds through it total.  I would wager a guess of something between 500-700 rounds.  I will send a full array of detailed pictures to interested parties.  Now for the explanation of the dogshit finish.  At some point during my dads ownership, he stowed the gun away for a long period of time and it got a little bit of surface rust on the slide serrations.  Instead of just using some super fine steel wool to buff em out, he bought some blue & rust remover.  He did not understand that this completely removes the bluing from a gun.  He apparently thought it would just take the rust spots off.  Not the brightest crayon in the box, my dad.  Once he saw his mistake, he doubled down and decided he would just remove all the blue from the gun, and then he'd reblue it himself.  Piece of cake right?  He failed miserably.  He ended up passing the gun down to me because he was ashamed of it.  Rightfully so.  I tried my hand at rebluing it, since I figured I couldn't destroy the finish any worse than he had.  I did my best, and got it looking better than he did at least.  Now it just looks heavily battleworn.  I considered having the thing professionally refinished, but I feel like I'd be sinking money into a gun I would ultimately not shoot that often. 10mm is too expensive for me anyway, I'm not a reloader. You may have seen some of my other posts though.  Basically I'm being bullied by the wife to sell off all the guns I don't need, and I'd very much like to receive a blowjob again sometime in the next decade, so I'm thinning out all the stuff I don't need.  No sentimental value here really, my dad passed me down some other guns that I will hold onto, so I can part with this one no problem.  I'm not certain what to price it at because of the finish.  But I see blued Colt Delta Elites being sold in the 800-900 range in decent condition on various gun auction sites.  I figure a good refinish of the gun could cost somewhere between 200 and 300 dollars. So lets take the lower end of 800, and subtract the higher end of 300 for a refinish, and come out around $500?  I don't know.  Make me an offer and I might go for it.  No box or paperwork, comes with one magazine.

title: For Sale/Trade:  FB Radom Vis 35
postcontent: SALE PENDING AS OF 12/2/2017.  1938 Polish Eagle FB Radom Vis 35. This gun contains no German markings at all. This is a pre-war model completely unmolested by the Nazis. These are becoming extremely hard to come by, and this gun is one instance where a lack of Nazi markings actually makes it more valuable. Most items of this time period fetch a higher dollar for any Nazi markings. Polish proof and inspection marks are all in the correct places. Stamped on both sides of the trigger guard bow and on the left side of the slide ahead of the decocking lever. This is all original parts to one gun, not pieced together. The serial numbers all match.  Barrel, slide, and frame. The only damage to the gun is one of the grip panels has a chunk missing. Replica grips can be found for 30 bucks.  Original grips can be found around $100.   Also, It appears a soldier inscribed his name on the slide and dated it. I tend to believe it was a soldier as the date etched into the slide (april 13th, 1945) was only a month before victory over europe day (may 8, 1945) Ive tried to find info on the name etched into the slide but have come up empty so far.  Feel free to dive into that rabbit hole on your own.  Light wear on the bluing. And the original white color fill is still mostly present.  This can be redone or removed easily.  The slide to frame fit is excellent, decocking lever, slide release, and mag release all in excellent working order. Mechanical function of the gun is pristine.I have fired the weapon just to test function.  There is a reason the Nazis made this one of their official sidearms during the war, they are extremely well made and surprisingly accurate.  If it werent a collectors item I probably would have made this one of my main range guns.  It's a great shooter not just for the time period but even now.  It rivals a well made 9mm 1911.  I'm not putting a price on it because there is such a fluctuation in the prices I see it being listed for.  On collectors websites people are selling these for upwards of 4 grand. Given the etching of mine I'm thinking something under 2 grand. If i could find some historical info on the name perhaps it would be worth more.  Please make an offer and we will negotiate from there.  I can tell you the average of all offers I've received is about 1500.  I'm treating this like an auction and just taking the best offer.  It's been up for about 2 months and I'm making a decision on Friday.High resolution video of the gun can be viewed at the following link.https://youtu.be/ngM3IIluAL0Make me an offer, cash or trade, lets see what happens.

Sides can be quickly removed without tools for hauling larger items.-Antique stamped steel tractor seat and spring mount (rides better than you’d think).-Kawasaki KZ440 rear fender and brake light.-Forward and mid footpegs.-New Bike Master AGM battery with larger capacity Ah than the original.-Evan Williams plastic coolant overflow reservoir with leather retainer.-New Duro HF903 dual sport tires front and rear.-Wiring cleaned up and certain power and ground wires were upgraded in size.-Front and rear turn signals to keep ya legal with the man.
